{"title_page": "Blanford's rosefinch", "text_new": "{{speciesbox\n| name = Blanford's rosefinch\n| image = Blanford's Rosefinch - Sela Pass - Arunachal Pradesh - India FJ0A8105 (34145295572).jpg\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22720546/0 |title=''Carpodacus rubescens'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| genus = Agraphospiza\n| parent_authority=Zuccon, Pr\u0177s-Jones, Rasmussen & Ericson, 2012\n| species = rubescens\n| authority = ([[William Thomas Blanford|Blanford]], 1872)\n| synonyms = \n}}\nThe '''Blanford's rosefinch''' or '''crimson rosefinch''' (''Agraphospiza rubescens'') is a species of [[finch]] in the family [[Fringillidae]].\nIt is found in [[Bhutan]], [[China]], [[India]], and [[Nepal]]. Its natural [[habitat]] is boreal [[forest]].\n\nBlanford's rosefinch was formerly placed in the [[genus]] ''[[Carpodacus]]'' with the other rosefinches. It was moved to the [[monotypic]] genus ''Agraphospiza''  based on the results from the phylogenetic analyses of mitochondrial and nuclear DNA sequences.<ref name=ioc>{{cite web| editor1-last=Gill | editor1-first=Frank | editor2-last=Donsker | editor2-first=David | title=Finches, euphonias | work= World Bird List Version 5.2| url=http://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/finches/ | publisher=International Ornithologists' Union| accessdate=5 June 2015 }}</ref><ref name=Zuccon2012>{{cite journal | last1=Zuccon | first1=Dario  | last2=Pr\u0177s-Jones | first2=Robert | last3=Rasmussen | first3=Pamela C. | last4=Ericson | first4=Per G.P. | year=2012 | title=The phylogenetic relationships and generic limits of finches (Fringillidae) | journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution | volume=62 | issue=2 | pages=581\u2013596 | doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2011.10.002 | url=http://www.nrm.se/download/18.9ff3752132fdaeccb6800010935/Zuccon%20et%20al%202012.pdf | pmid=22023825}}</ref> It differs from rosefinches in the genus ''Carpodacus''. Both sexes have unstreaked plumage, the bill is thinner and less conical, the wings are more pointed and it has a shorter tail.<ref name=Zuccon2012/>\n\nIts common name commemorates the [[England|English]] zoologist [[William Thomas Blanford]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Beolens|first=Bo|title=Whose Bird? Men and Women Commemorated in the Common Names of Birds|year=2003|publisher=Christopher Helm|location=London|page=55|author2=Watkins, Michael}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q27075736}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:rosefinch, Blanford's}}\n[[Category:Finches|Blanford's rosefinch]]\n[[Category:Birds of Nepal]]\n[[Category:Birds of Bhutan]]\n[[Category:Birds of Central China]]\n[[Category:Birds of Yunnan]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1872|Blanford's rosefinch]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n\n\n{{Fringillidae-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{speciesbox\n| name = Blanford's rosefinch\n| image = Blanford's Rosefinch - Sela Pass - Arunachal Pradesh - India FJ0A8105 (34145295572).jpg\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22720546/0 |title=''Carpodacus rubescens'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| genus = Agraphospiza\n| parent_authority=Zuccon, Pr\u0177s-Jones, Rasmussen & Ericson, 2012\n| species = rubescens\n| authority = ([[William Thomas Blanford|Blanford]], 1872)\n| synonyms = \n}}\nThe '''Blanford's rosefinch''' or '''crimson rosefinch''' (''Agraphospiza rubescens'') is a species of [[finch]] in the [[Fringillidae]] family.\nIt is found in [[Bhutan]], [[China]], [[India]], and [[Nepal]]. Its natural [[habitat]] is boreal [[forest]]s.\n\nBlanford's rosefinch was formerly placed in the [[genus]] ''[[Carpodacus]]'' with the other rosefinches. It was moved to the [[monotypic]] genus ''Agraphospiza''  based on the results from the phylogenetic analyses of mitochondrial and nuclear DNA sequences.<ref name=ioc>{{cite web| editor1-last=Gill | editor1-first=Frank | editor2-last=Donsker | editor2-first=David | title=Finches, euphonias | work= World Bird List Version 5.2| url=http://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/finches/ | publisher=International Ornithologists' Union| accessdate=5 June 2015 }}</ref><ref name=Zuccon2012>{{cite journal | last1=Zuccon | first1=Dario  | last2=Pr\u0177s-Jones | first2=Robert | last3=Rasmussen | first3=Pamela C. | last4=Ericson | first4=Per G.P. | year=2012 | title=The phylogenetic relationships and generic limits of finches (Fringillidae) | journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution | volume=62 | issue=2 | pages=581\u2013596 | doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2011.10.002 | url=http://www.nrm.se/download/18.9ff3752132fdaeccb6800010935/Zuccon%20et%20al%202012.pdf | pmid=22023825}}</ref> It differs from rosefinches in the genus ''Carpodacus''. Both sexes have unstreaked plumage, the bill is thinner and less conical, the wings are more pointed and it has a shorter tail.<ref name=Zuccon2012/>\n\nIts common name commemorates the [[England|English]] zoologist [[William Thomas Blanford]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Beolens|first=Bo|title=Whose Bird? Men and Women Commemorated in the Common Names of Birds|year=2003|publisher=Christopher Helm|location=London|page=55|author2=Watkins, Michael}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q27075736}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:rosefinch, Blanford's}}\n[[Category:Finches|Blanford's rosefinch]]\n[[Category:Birds of Nepal]]\n[[Category:Birds of Bhutan]]\n[[Category:Birds of Central China]]\n[[Category:Birds of Yunnan]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1872|Blanford's rosefinch]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n\n\n{{Fringillidae-stub}}\n", "name_user": "WolfmanSF", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blanford%27s_rosefinch"}
{"title_page": "1976 Ontario Liberal Party leadership election", "text_new": "{{Infobox leadership election\n| party     = Ontario Liberal Party\n| colour    = {{Canadian party colour|ON|Liberal}}\n| year      = 1976\n| logo      = \n| date      = January 24\u201325, 1976\n| location  = [[Sheraton Centre Toronto Hotel|Four Seasons Sheraton Hotel]], [[Toronto]], Ontario\n| winner    = [[Stuart Lyon Smith|Stuart Smith]] \n| replaces  = [[Robert Nixon (politician)|Robert Nixon]] \n| numcands  = 6 (7)\n| ballots   = 3 \n| entryfee  = \n| spendcap  = \n}}\nThe '''Ontario Liberal Party''' held a '''leadership election in 1976''' on January 24\u201325 to replace [[Robert Nixon (politician)|Robert Nixon]]. Nixon had announced his retirement after the 1975 election in which the [[Ontario Liberal Party|Liberal Party]] was reduced from Official Opposition status in the [[Legislative Assembly of Ontario]] to being the third party. [[Stuart Lyon Smith|Stuart Smith]] was elected as the party's new leader.\n\n==Background==\nAfter the disappointing results of the [[1975 Ontario general election|1975 provincial election]], Robert Nixon announced his resignation on September 30, 1975. He said, \"the best interests of our party will be served if we contest the next election under new leadership.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Best for party that I go Nixon says |newspaper=Toronto Star |date=September 30, 1975 |page=A1}}</ref>\n\nPotential candidates began announcing their candidacy soon after. First to announce was [[Larry Condon]], a member of the federal parliament (MP) from [[Middlesex (electoral district)|Middlesex\u2014London\u2014Lambton]]. Condon, who had served as mayor of [[Strathroy-Caradoc|Strathroy, Ontario]], said that he empathized with the working man and would seek grassroots support.<ref>{{cite news |title=At Queen's Park: Condon enter Liberal leadership race |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |date=October 30, 1975 |page=5}}</ref> Next to join the campaign was Edward Culp, a Toronto teacher who had also run in the [[1973 Ontario Liberal Party leadership election|1973 Liberal leadership election]]. Culp told reporters that he had \"earned the right to be treated as a serious candidate\". He described himself as a 'left-nationalist'.<ref>{{cite news |title=Inside Metro: Teacher bids for Liberal leadership |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |date=November 5, 1975 |page=5}}</ref> He was the first to drop out of the race in early January 1976.<ref>{{cite news |title=No clear-cut favorite has emerged as Liberal hopefuls race down stretch |newspaper=Toronto Star |date=January 17, 1976 |page=A3}}</ref> Third to announce on November 11 was Michael Houlton, another fringe candidate from the 1973 race. Houlton, who worked in advertising decided to try again although his main goal seemed to be to promote his advertising business.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ad man 3rd candidate for Robert Nixon's job |newspaper=Toronto Star |date=November 11, 1975 |page=A7}}</ref>\n\nOn November 14, the first serious candidate to enter the race was [[Stuart Lyon Smith|Stuart Smith]], a 37-year-old Montreal-born psychiatrist.<ref>{{cite news |title=Liberal contender presents self as man to stand up to Lewis |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |date=November 14, 1975 |page=33}}</ref> Smith, who was elected as a [[Member of Provincial Parliament (Ontario)|Member of Provincial Parliament]] (MPP) in [[Hamilton West (electoral district)|Hamilton West]] in 1975 was well-spoken and articulate. Provincial Liberals thought that Smith reminded them of [[Pierre Trudeau]].<ref name=\"carppa1976\">{{cite book |title=Canadian Annual Review of Politics and Public Affairs (1976) |editor=John Saywell |author=Peter Oliver |publisher=University of Toronto Press |location=Toronto |year=1977 |pages=169\u2013170}}</ref> [[David Peterson]] announced his candidacy on December 12 but he had been campaigning for at least a month before that. The 31-year-old businessman who had been elected in [[London Centre]] in 1975 said that he had support from ten caucus members including [[Edward Sargent]], [[Jack Riddell|John Riddell]] and [[Sean Conway]].<ref>{{cite news |title=10 caucus members support him as Liberal leader, Peterson says |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |date=December 13, 1975 |page=5}}</ref> Rounding out the candidates were [[Mark MacGuigan]], a 44-year-old federal MP from Windsor and [[Albert Roy]], a 36-year-old MPP from Ottawa.\n\nOther people whose names were cited as possible candidates were MPPs [[T. Patrick Reid|Patrick Reid]], [[Jim Bullbrook]], [[Jim Breithaupt]] and MPs [[Norman Cafik]], [[John Roberts (Canadian politician)|John Roberts]] and [[Anthony Abbott]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Potential Ontario Liberal leaders test their support |first=peter |last=Mosher |newspaper=Globe and Mail |date=November 10, 1975 |page=8}}</ref> Some Liberals including [[Donald Deacon]] tried to recruit former federal finance minister [[John Turner]] for the leadership election, but he declined.<ref>{{cite news |title=Turner and Campbell still possible choices |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |date=January 15, 1976 |page=59}}</ref>\n\nPeterson spent the most money on his campaign at $54,415, followed by Roy at $50,000, MacGuigan at $40,000. Smith spent the least at $29,866.<ref name=tears>{{cite news |title=Tears for Mark MacGuigan as $40,000 political try fails |newspaper=Toronto Star |date=January 26, 1976 |page=A3}}</ref><ref name=\"carppa1976\"/>\n\n==Convention==\nOn January 23, 1976, about 2,000 Liberal delegates gathered at the [[Fairmont Royal York|Royal York Hotel]] to give Nixon a rousing tribute. Nixon, who refused to give any of the four main contenders an endorsement, said he would remain in the Legislature as a regular member.<ref>{{cite news |title=2,000 say goodbye as Nixon bows out for 'new generation' |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |date=January 24, 1976 |pages=1\u20132}}</ref> The speeches took place on Saturday. Although no one stood out, Peterson's speech was seen as stilted and over rehearsed.<ref name=machine>{{cite news |title=Peterson's machine stalls but it brought him close |newspaper=Toronto Star |date=January 26, 1976 |page=A3}}</ref> He later characterized it as the \"worst speech in modern political history\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Peterson runs hard to stay ahead |last=Palango |first=Paul |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |date=February 16, 1982 |page=P4}}</ref> After the first ballot Smith was in the lead followed by Peterson, Roy and MacGuigan. MacGuigan elected to drop out after the first ballot even though he could have stayed for another round. He refused to make any endorsements.<ref name=tears/> After the second ballot, Roy was dropped. Peterson's team tried hard to get him to endorse their candidate but their push appeared to irritate Roy and he refused to make any endorsement.<ref name=machine/> On the third ballot Smith narrowly won by 45 votes.\n\nDuring the convention, there was not much difference in policy between the candidates. Some delegates felt that Peterson was too young to be leader and others were dissuaded because he reminded them of current [[Progressive Conservative Party of Ontario|Tory]] Premier, [[Bill Davis]]. Smith presented a different style which provided a marked contrast from Peterson. He won on his 'intellectual qualities' and urban appeal. Smith presented himself as the party's chance for power. He said, \"the delegates are going to ask, 'Could he run this province? He's got long hair, he's a shrink, he's Jewish, and he's from Quebec.' ... Well, you know, trying something different can be the highlight of a person's life.\"<ref name=\"carppa1976\"/>\n\n==Aftermath==\nSmith's competence as leader was soon tested in the Legislature. In his first session, during the [[Speech from the Throne]], the [[Ontario New Democratic Party]] (NDP) made a motion condemning the government's position. Smith, without consulting his party, made a sub-amendment to the NDP motion which also condemned the government in much the same language. Since this was a minority government it would have brought down the government. Smith was pilloried in the house the next day which was exacerbated due to the fact that he was out of town for another engagement. In the end the NDP and the Liberals defeated the government 70 to 48 on the Liberal amendment but then the Liberals voted with the Tories to defeat the similar NDP amendment. Smith tried to save face by stating \"We voted for our own amendment to register disapproval with government policy. We voted against the NDP amendment simply to avoid an election.\"<ref name=\"carppa1976\"/>\n\nThe Liberals under Smith regained status as official opposition after the 1977 election in another minority parliament but suffered disappointment in 1981 when the Tories regained a majority. Smith resigned after his second election defeat after six years as leader.\n\n==Ballot results==\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"5\" cellspacing=\"0\"\n|+ '''Delegate support by ballot'''\n|-\n! colspan = \"1\" | Candidate\n! colspan = \"2\" | 1st ballot\n! colspan = \"2\" | 2nd ballot\n! colspan = \"2\" | 3rd ballot\n|-\n|Name \n|Votes cast \n| % \n|Votes cast \n| % \n|Votes cast \n| % \n|-\n| '''[[Stuart Lyon Smith|Stuart Smith]]'''\n| 629\n| 32.0\n| 742\n| 38.5\n| '''998'''\n| '''51.2'''\n|-\n| [[David Peterson]]\n| 518\n| 26.4\n| 673\n| 34.9\n| 953\n| 48.8\n|-\n| [[Albert Roy]]\n| 469\n| 23.9\n| 513\n| 26.6\n| style=\"text-align:left;background:lightblue\" colspan = \"2\" |No endorsement\n|-\n| [[Mark MacGuigan]]\n| 308\n| 15.7\n| style=\"text-align:left;background:lightgreen\" colspan = \"4\" |No endorsement\n|-\n| [[Larry Condon]]\n| 37\n| 1.9\n| style=\"text-align:left;background:lightblue\" colspan = \"4\" |No endorsement\n|-\n| Michael Houlton\n| 4\n| 0.2\n| style=\"text-align:left;background:lightgreen\" colspan = \"4\" |No endorsement\n|-\n|Total\n| 1,965\n| 100.0\n| 1,928\n| 100.0\n| 1,951\n| 100.0\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ontario Liberal Party Leadership Convention, 1976}}\n[[Category:1976 elections in Canada]]\n[[Category:1976 in Toronto]]\n[[Category:Leaders of the Ontario Liberal Party|#1976]]\n[[Category:Ontario Liberal Party leadership elections|1976]]\n[[Category:January 1976 events in Canada]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox leadership election\n| party     = Ontario Liberal Party\n| colour    = {{Canadian party colour|ON|Liberal}}\n| year      = 1976\n| logo      = \n| date      = January 24\u201325, 1976\n| location  = [[Sheraton Centre Toronto Hotel|Four Seasons Sheraton Hotel]], [[Toronto]], Ontario\n| winner    = [[Stuart Lyon Smith|Stuart Smith]] \n| replaces  = [[Robert Nixon (politician)|Robert Nixon]] \n| numcands  = 6 (7)\n| ballots   = 3 \n| entryfee  = \n| spendcap  = \n}}\nThe '''Ontario Liberal Party''' held a '''leadership election in 1976''' on January 24\u201325 to replace [[Robert Nixon (politician)|Robert Nixon]]. Nixon had announced his retirement after the 1975 election in which the [[Ontario Liberal Party|Liberal Party]] was reduced from Official Opposition status in the [[Legislative Assembly of Ontario]] to being the third party. [[Stuart Lyon Smith|Stuart Smith]] was elected as the party's new leader.\n\n==Background==\nAfter the disappointing results of the [[1975 Ontario general election|1975 provincial election]], Robert Nixon announced his resignation on September 30, 1975. He said, \"the best interests of our party will be served if we contest the next election under new leadership.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Best for party that I go Nixon says |newspaper=Toronto Star |date=September 30, 1975 |page=A1}}</ref>\n\nPotential candidates began announcing their candidacy soon after. First to announce was [[Larry Condon]], a member of the federal parliament (MP) from [[Middlesex (electoral district)|Middlesex\u2014London\u2014Lambton]]. Condon, who had served as mayor of [[Strathroy-Caradoc|Strathroy, Ontario]], said that he empathized with the working man and would seek grassroots support.<ref>{{cite news |title=At Queen's Park: Condon enter Liberal leadership race |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |date=October 30, 1975 |page=5}}</ref> Next to join the campaign was Edward Culp, a Toronto teacher who had also run in the [[1973 Ontario Liberal Party leadership election|1973 Liberal leadership election]]. Culp told reporters that he had \"earned the right to be treated as a serious candidate\". He described himself as a 'left-nationalist'.<ref>{{cite news |title=Inside Metro: Teacher bids for Liberal leadership |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |date=November 5, 1975 |page=5}}</ref> He was the first to drop out of the race in early January 1976.<ref>{{cite news |title=No clear-cut favorite has emerged as Liberal hopefuls race down stretch |newspaper=Toronto Star |date=January 17, 1976 |page=A3}}</ref> Third to announce on November 11 was Michael Houlton, another fringe candidate from the 1973 race. Houlton, who worked in advertising decided to try again although his main goal seemed to be to promote his advertising business.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ad man 3rd candidate for Robert Nixon's job |newspaper=Toronto Star |date=November 11, 1975 |page=A7}}</ref>\n\nOn November 14, the first serious candidate to enter the race was [[Stuart Lyon Smith|Stuart Smith]], a 37-year-old Montreal-born psychiatrist.<ref>{{cite news |title=Liberal contender presents self as man to stand up to Lewis |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |date=November 14, 1975 |page=33}}</ref> Smith, who was elected as a [[Member of Provincial Parliament (Ontario)|Member of Provincial Parliament]] (MPP) in [[Hamilton West (electoral district)|Hamilton West]] in 1975 was well-spoken and articulate. Provincial Liberals thought that Smith reminded them of [[Pierre Trudeau]].<ref name=\"carppa1976\">{{cite book |title=Canadian Annual Review of Politics and Public Affairs (1976) |editor=John Saywell |author=Peter Oliver |publisher=University of Toronto Press |location=Toronto |year=1977 |pages=169\u2013170}}</ref> [[David Peterson]] announced his candidacy on December 12 but he had been campaigning for at least a month before that. The 31-year-old businessman who had been elected in [[London Centre]] in 1975 said that he had support from ten caucus members including [[Edward Sargent]], [[Jack Riddell|John Riddell]] and [[Sean Conway]].<ref>{{cite news |title=10 caucus members support him as Liberal leader, Peterson says |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |date=December 13, 1975 |page=5}}</ref> Rounding out the candidates were [[Mark MacGuigan]], a 44-year-old federal MP from Windsor and [[Albert Roy]], a 36-year-old MPP from Ottawa.\n\nOther people whose names were cited as possible candidates were MPPs [[T. Patrick Reid|Patrick Reid]], [[Jim Bullbrook]], [[Jim Breithaupt]] and MPs [[Norman Cafik]], [[John Roberts (Canadian politician)|John Roberts]] and [[Anthony Abbott]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Potential Ontario Liberal leaders test their support |first=peter |last=Mosher |newspaper=Globe and Mail |date=November 10, 1975 |page=8}}</ref> Some Liberals including [[Donald Deacon]] tried to recruit former federal finance minister [[John Turner]] for the leadership election, but he declined.<ref>{{cite news |title=Turner and Campbell still possible choices |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |date=January 15, 1976 |page=59}}</ref>\n\nPeterson spent the most money on his campaign at $54,415, followed by Roy at $50,000, MacGuigan at $40,000. Smith spent the least at $29,866.<ref name=tears>{{cite news |title=Tears for Mark MacGuigan as $40,000 political try fails |newspaper=Toronto Star |date=January 26, 1976 |page=A3}}</ref><ref name=\"carppa1976\"/>\n\n==Convention==\nOn January 23, 1976, about 2,000 Liberal delegates gathered at the [[Fairmont Royal York|Royal York Hotel]] to give Nixon a rousing tribute. Nixon, who refused to give any of the four main contenders an endorsement, said he would remain in the Legislature as a regular member.<ref>{{cite news |title=2,000 say goodbye as Nixon bows out for 'new generation' |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |date=January 24, 1976 |pages=1\u20132}}</ref> The speeches took place on Saturday. Although no one stood out, Peterson's speech was seen as stilted and over rehearsed.<ref name=machine>{{cite news |title=Peterson's machine stalls but it brought him close |newspaper=Toronto Star |date=January 26, 1976 |page=A3}}</ref> He later characterized it as the \"worst speech in modern political history\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Peterson runs hard to stay ahead |last=Palango |first=Paul |newspaper=The Globe and Mail |date=February 16, 1982 |page=P4}}</ref> After the first ballot Smith was in the lead followed by Peterson, Roy and MacGuigan. MacGuigan elected to drop out after the first ballot even though he could have stayed for another round. He refused to make any endorsements.<ref name=tears/> After the second ballot, Roy was dropped. Peterson's team tried hard to get him to endorse their candidate but their push appeared to irritate Roy and he refused to make any endorsement.<ref name=machine/> On the third ballot Smith narrowly won by 45 votes.\n\nDuring the convention, there was not much difference in policy between the candidates. Some delegates felt that Peterson was too young to be leader and others were dissuaded because he reminded them of current [[Progressive Conservative Party of Ontario|Tory]] Premier, [[Bill Davis]]. Smith presented a different style which provided a marked contrast from Peterson. He won on his 'intellectual qualities' and urban appeal. Smith presented himself as the party's chance for power. He said, \"the delegates are going to ask, 'Could he run this province? He's got long hair, he's a shrink, he's Jewish, and he's from Quebec.' ... Well, you know, trying something different can be the highlight of a person's life.\"<ref name=\"carppa1976\"/>\n\n==Aftermath==\nSmith's competence as leader was soon tested in the Legislature. In his first session, during the [[Speech from the Throne]], the [[Ontario New Democratic Party]] (NDP) made a motion condemning the government's position. Smith, without consulting his party, made a sub-amendment to the NDP motion which also condemned the government in much the same language. Since this was a minority government it would have brought down the government. Smith was pilloried in the house the next day which was exacerbated due to the fact that he was out of town for another engagement. In the end the NDP and the Liberals defeated the government 70 to 48 on the Liberal amendment but then the Liberals voted with the Tories to defeat the similar NDP amendment. Smith tried to save face by stating \"We voted for our own amendment to register disapproval with government policy. We voted against the NDP amendment simply to avoid an election.\"<ref name=\"carppa1976\"/>\n\nThe Liberals under Smith regained status as official opposition after the 1977 election in another minority parliament but suffered disappointment in 1981 when the Tories regained a majority. Smith resigned after his second election defeat after six years as leader.\n\n==Ballot results==\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"5\" cellspacing=\"0\"\n|+ '''Delegate support by ballot'''\n|-\n! colspan = \"1\" | Candidate\n! colspan = \"2\" | 1st ballot\n! colspan = \"2\" | 2nd ballot\n! colspan = \"2\" | 3rd ballot\n|-\n|Name \n|Votes cast \n| % \n|Votes cast \n| % \n|Votes cast \n| % \n|-\n| '''[[Stuart Lyon Smith|Stuart Smith]]'''\n| 629\n| 32.0\n| 742\n| 38.5\n| '''998'''\n| '''51.2'''\n|-\n| [[David Peterson]]\n| 518\n| 26.4\n| 673\n| 34.9\n| 953\n| 48.8\n|-\n| [[Albert Roy]]\n| 469\n| 23.9\n| 513\n| 26.6\n| style=\"text-align:left;background:lightblue\" colspan = \"2\" |No endorsement\n|-\n| [[Mark MacGuigan]]\n| 308\n| 15.7\n| style=\"text-align:left;background:lightgreen\" colspan = \"4\" |No endorsement\n|-\n| [[Larry Condon]]\n| 37\n| 1.9\n| style=\"text-align:left;background:lightblu