{"title_page": "Ten Percent Ring", "text_new": "The '''Ten-Percent Ring''' was a title given by the editors of ''[[The Tombstone Epitaph]]'' in 1881 to [[Johnny Behan]] and his friends for stealing about ten percent of the local [[Tombstone, Arizona]] taxes in the 1880s. Milt Joyce, owner of the Oriental Saloon and chairman of [[Cochise County, Arizona]] supervisors was also seen as a leader of the Ten Percent Ring. The ''Tombstone Epitaph'' was started by [[John Clum]] in 1880. <ref>The Tombstone Epitaph, December 25, 1881.</ref> The newspaper outlined the corruption charges of Johnny Behan the Cochise County [[sheriff]]. <ref>James Covington Hancock Papers, Arizona Historical Society, Tucson.</ref> <ref>Wyatt Earp: A Vigilante Life, Andrew C. Isenberg page 241</ref> When Johnny Behan was the Cochise County sheriff one of his duties was collecting prostitution, gambling, liquor, and theater taxes. As part of his pay, he received 10% of all proceeds collected. There was much talk in the town about the [[Graft (politics)|graft]] [[political corruption]] of the sheriff. For this many saw Behan as the head of the Ten Percent Ring and a friend of the outlaw [[Cochise County Cowboys]]. Others accused of membership in the ring was Artemus Fay (?-1906), owner of the Tombstone's first newspaper, the ''Tombstone Nugget'' and Harry Wood a writer for the ''Nugget'' and an under-sheriff of Behan. Behan so focused on taxes, that he was very soft on crime. Soon after Behan became sheriff, [[Virgil Earp]] was appointed Tombstone city marshal and had is brothers [[Wyatt Earp]] and [[Morgan Earp]] become special deputy policemen. Behan and the Earps were at conflict as Behan supported the outlaw [[Ike Clanton|Clanton]] and [[Frank McLaury|McLaury]] families.<ref>{{cite book|last=Urban|first=William|title=Wyatt Earp: The O.K. Corral and the Law of the American West |year=2003|publisher=The Rosen Publishing Group, Inc|url=https://archive.org/details/wyattearpokcorra00urba|url-access=registration|page=[https://archive.org/details/wyattearpokcorra00urba/page/67 67]}}</ref><ref name=butler /> On January 31, 1882, Behan was arrested for collecting bills totaling $300 twice, arraigned in front of [[William Henry Stilwell|Justice Stilwell]], and discharged due to a technicality.<ref name=union14140>{{cite web|publisher=Sacramento Daily Union|volume=14 |number=140 |date=2 February 1882 |accessdate=16 October 2014 |title=Discharged from Custody Cowboys Surrendered|url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SDU18820202.2.7.3&srpos=48&e=-------en--20--41--txt-txIN-tombstone+earp------#}}</ref> Behan failed to win re-election as sheriff in November of 1882, he would not serve as a peace officer again. He later was appointed as the warden of the [[Yuma Territorial Prison]] and had various other government jobs until his death in 1912.<ref>[https://www.geni.com/people/Johnny-Behan-Sheriff-Cochise-County-Arizona-Territory/6000000010967709781 geni.com Johnny Behan] </ref><ref>Murder in Tombstone: The Forgotten Trial of Wyatt Earp, By Steven Lubet, page 38</ref><ref>I Meet Mrs. Earp, I Married Wyatt Earp, by Josephine Sarah Marcus Earp. Edited by Glenn G. Boyer. Tucson: University of Arizona Press, 1976.</ref><ref name=butler>{{cite book|last=Butler|first=Anne M.|title=Daughters of Joy, Sisters of Misery: Prostitutes in the American West, 1865\u201390|year=1987|publisher=University of Illinois Press|location=Urbana, Ill.|isbn=978-0-252-01466-6|edition=paperback|url=https://archive.org/details/daughtersofjoysi00butl}}</ref><ref>Doc Holliday: The Life and Legend, By Gary L. Roberts, page </ref> Milt Joyce, departed Tombstone in 1883. On October 10, 1880 Joyce and [[Doc Holliday]] had a shoot out at the Oriental. Joyce died in 1889 at the age of 42 in [[San Francisco]], he was the owner of the Baldwin Billiard Parlor in 1883 and later the Cafe Royal in San Francisco.<ref>[http://www.americancowboychronicles.com/2019/12/milt-joyce-western-pioneer.html americancowboychronicles.com Milt Joyce]</ref><ref>The Daily Alta California, November 30th, 1889</ref>\n\n==Popular culture==\nThe Ten Percent Ring was a key figure in the much-fictionized TV series ''[[The Life and Legend of Wyatt Earp]]'', starring [[Hugh O'Brian]] in the starring role. [[Steve Brodie (actor)|Steve Brodie]] played Behan in nine episodes of the series.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0479017/?ref_=tt_cl_t9|title=Lash LaRue|publisher=[[Internet Movie Data Base]]|accessdate=10 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Gunfight at the O.K. Corral]]\n*[[Confederate Arizona]]\n*[[Arizona Territory in the American Civil War]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Wild West}}\n{{Cochise County Conflict}}\n\n\n[[Category:History of Cochise County, Arizona]]\n[[Category:Arizona folklore]]\n[[Category:Crime in Arizona Territory]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1881]]\n[[Category:Cochise County conflict]]\n[[Category:Outlaws of the American Old West]]\n[[Category:Gangs in Arizona]]\n", "text_old": "The '''Ten-Percent Ring''' was a title given by the editors of ''[[The Tombstone Epitaph]]'' in 1881 to [[Johnny Behan]] and his friends for stealing about ten percent of the local [[Tombstone, Arizona]] taxes in the 1880s. Milt Joyce, owner of the Oriental Saloon and chairman of [[Cochise County, Arizona]] supervisors was also seen as a leader of the Ten Percent Ring. The ''Tombstone Epitaph'' was started by [[John Clum]] in 1880. <ref>The Tombstone Epitaph, December 25, 1881.</ref> The newspaper outlined the corruption charges of Johnny Behan the Cochise County [[sheriff]]. <ref>James Covington Hancock Papers, Arizona Historical Society, Tucson.</ref> <ref>Wyatt Earp: A Vigilante Life, Andrew C. Isenberg page 241</ref> When Johnny Behan was the Cochise County sheriff one of his duties was collecting prostitution, gambling, liquor, and theater taxes. As part of his pay, he received 10% of all proceeds collected. There was much talk in the town about the [[Graft (politics)|graft]] [[political corruption]] of the sheriff. For this many saw Behan as the head of the Ten Percent Ring and a friend of the outlaw [[Cochise County Cowboys]]. Others accused of members of the ring was Artemus Fay, owner of the Tombstone's first newspaper, the ''Tombstone Nugget'' and Harry Wood a writer for the ''Nugget'' and an under-sheriff of Behan. Behan so focuseded on taxes, that he was very soft on crime. Soon after Behan became sheriff, [[Virgil Earp]] was appointed Tombstone city marshal and had is brothers [[Wyatt Earp]] and [[Morgan Earp]] become special deputy policemen. Behan and the Earps were at conflict as Behan supported the outlaw [[Ike Clanton|Clanton]] and [[Frank McLaury|McLaury]] families.<ref>{{cite book|last=Urban|first=William|title=Wyatt Earp: The O.K. Corral and the Law of the American West |year=2003|publisher=The Rosen Publishing Group, Inc|url=https://archive.org/details/wyattearpokcorra00urba|url-access=registration|page=[https://archive.org/details/wyattearpokcorra00urba/page/67 67]}}</ref><ref name=butler /> On January 31, 1882, Behan was arrested for collecting bills totaling $300 twice, arraigned in front of [[William Henry Stilwell|Justice Stilwell]], and discharged due to a technicality.<ref name=union14140>{{cite web|publisher=Sacramento Daily Union|volume=14 |number=140 |date=2 February 1882 |accessdate=16 October 2014 |title=Discharged from Custody Cowboys Surrendered|url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&d=SDU18820202.2.7.3&srpos=48&e=-------en--20--41--txt-txIN-tombstone+earp------#}}</ref> Behan failed to win re-election as sheriff in November of 1882, he would not serve as a peace officer again. He later was appointed as the warden of the [[Yuma Territorial Prison]] and had various other government jobs until his death in 1912.<ref>[https://www.geni.com/people/Johnny-Behan-Sheriff-Cochise-County-Arizona-Territory/6000000010967709781 geni.com Johnny Behan] </ref><ref>Murder in Tombstone: The Forgotten Trial of Wyatt Earp, By Steven Lubet, page 38</ref><ref>I Meet Mrs. Earp, I Married Wyatt Earp, by Josephine Sarah Marcus Earp. Edited by Glenn G. Boyer. Tucson: University of Arizona Press, 1976.</ref><ref name=butler>{{cite book|last=Butler|first=Anne M.|title=Daughters of Joy, Sisters of Misery: Prostitutes in the American West, 1865\u201390|year=1987|publisher=University of Illinois Press|location=Urbana, Ill.|isbn=978-0-252-01466-6|edition=paperback|url=https://archive.org/details/daughtersofjoysi00butl}}</ref><ref>Doc Holliday: The Life and Legend, By Gary L. Roberts, page </ref> Milt Joyce, departed Tombstone in 1883. On October 10, 1880 Joyce and [[Doc Holliday]] had a shoot out at the Oriental. Joyce died in 1889 at the age of 42 in [[San Francisco]], he was the owner of the Baldwin Billiard Parlor in 1883 and later the Cafe Royal in San Francisco.<ref>[http://www.americancowboychronicles.com/2019/12/milt-joyce-western-pioneer.html americancowboychronicles.com Milt Joyce]</ref><ref>The Daily Alta California, November 30th, 1889</ref>\n\n==Popular culture==\nThe Ten Percent Ring was a key figure in the much-fictionized TV series ''[[The Life and Legend of Wyatt Earp]]'', starring [[Hugh O'Brian]] in the starring role. [[Steve Brodie (actor)|Steve Brodie]] played Behan in nine episodes of the series.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0479017/?ref_=tt_cl_t9|title=Lash LaRue|publisher=[[Internet Movie Data Base]]|accessdate=10 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Gunfight at the O.K. Corral]]\n*[[Confederate Arizona]]\n*[[Arizona Territory in the American Civil War]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Wild West}}\n{{Cochise County Conflict}}\n\n\n[[Category:History of Cochise County, Arizona]]\n[[Category:Arizona folklore]]\n[[Category:Crime in Arizona Territory]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1881]]\n[[Category:Cochise County conflict]]\n[[Category:Outlaws of the American Old West]]\n[[Category:Gangs in Arizona]]\n", "name_user": "Telecineguy", "label": "safe"